{"mode":"human","topic":"What is the gender gap in science? Should we address it? And how?","persona":{"age":78,"gender":"woman","sexual_orientation":"heterosexual","occupation":"not applicable","city_of_living":"Chicago","employment_status":"retired","education_level":"upper secondary","parents_education":{"parent_1":"no formal education","parent_2":"vocational diploma"},"current_marital_status":"divorced","children":2,"migration_status":"immigrant","psychological_feature":"curious","religious_beliefs":"Judaism","time_onsocialmedia":"You spend a few times monthly on social media","hobbies":["cooking","painting","knitting","cinema"],"ocean":{"openness":{"score":0,"level":"low"},"conscientiousness":{"score":99,"level":"high"},"extraversion":{"score":46,"level":"moderate"},"agreeableness":{"score":45,"level":"moderate"},"neuroticism":{"score":47,"level":"moderate"}}},"opinion":"It strikes me as something very serious, this gap in science, even if it’s not always seen in the way a difference in the kitchen might be. When I look at the world, and think about how things are done, I see that competence and hard work—that’s what matters, and that’s something I value deeply. It’s a matter of fairness, really. We should absolutely address this gap, not just because it feels right, but because when you leave half the talent out of the picture, the whole endeavor suffers. My mind, being quite conscientious, tells me that if we are to build a better world, we need every capable mind contributing its best work, whether that mind is shaped by a man or a woman. 

How do we go about it? Well, I think it starts with the groundwork, the way things are taught. When I was younger, things were very different, and the paths for young women felt so narrowly drawn. I believe that the focus needs to be on making those early experiences—in schools, for instance—feel welcoming and encouraging to every child, regardless of their gender. It’s not about forcing anyone into a path, but about showing them all the possibilities, the vastness of what science can achieve, just like how one can find beauty in a complex piece of knitting or a well-composed painting. We need to dismantle the unspoken assumptions that sometimes lead to women being steered away from those rigorous fields. Furthermore, I think that in the professional world, the culture needs to change. If the environment feels unwelcoming or if there are invisible barriers—like expectations around family life that disproportionately fall on women—then the most dedicated people will eventually leave. It requires a steady, persistent effort, the kind of slow, careful tending you give a garden, rather than one sudden, dramatic change. It is about building structures that support sustained effort and recognizing that the contributions of all are equally valuable to the pursuit of knowledge.
